Owing to their unique potential to ferment carbohydrates, both homo- and heterofermentative lactic acid bacteria (LAB) are widely used in the food industry. Deciphering the genetic bases that determine the LAB fermentation type, and hence carbohydrate utilization, is paramount to optimize LAB industrial processes. Deep sequencing of 24 LAB species and comparison with 32 publicly available genome sequences provided a comparative data set including five major LAB genera for further analysis. Phylogenomic reconstruction confirmed Leuconostoc and Pediococcus species as independently emerging from the Lactobacillus genus, within one of the three phylogenetic clades identified. These clades partially grouped LABs according to their fermentation types, suggesting some metabolic capabilities were independently acquired during LAB evolution. In order to apply a genome-wide association study (GWAS) at the multigene family level, utilization of 49 carbohydrates was also profiled for these 56 LAB species. GWAS results indicated that obligately heterofermentative species lack 1-phosphofructokinase, required for D-mannose degradation in the homofermentative pathway. Heterofermentative species were found to often contain the araBAD operon, involved in L-arabinose degradation, which is important for heterofermentation. Taken together, our results provide helpful insights into the genetic determinants of LAB carbohydrate metabolism, and opens for further experimental research, aiming at validating the role of these candidate genes for industrial applications.

Genomic Encyclopedia of Type Strains, Phase I: one thousand microbial genomes (KMG) project. The goal of the Genomic Encyclopedia of Bacteria and Archaea (GEBA) initiative is to sequence genomes to fill phylogenetic gaps, generating reference genomes for every major and minor group of bacteria and archaea. Currently sequenced genomes have provided highly uneven coverage of the type strain material present in public culture collections. The Project is focused on the study, understanding and exploitation of aerobic and respiratory metabolism in wild and mutant strains of Lactobacillus casei group. In particular, the effect of aerobic and respiratory metabolism on the growth, stress tolerance, proteomic and metabolic profiles has been investigated in different strains of L. casei group, in order to improve survival of starter and probiotic cultures and to enhance the nutritional and technological properties of fermented foods. A complex approach based on transcriptomic, proteomic and metabolomic analyses has been used to carry out all research activities.

Comprehensive reference data is essential for accurate taxonomic and functional characterisation of the human gut microbiome. Here we present the Unified Human Gastrointestinal Genome (UHGG) collection, a resource combining 286,997 genomes representing 4,644 prokaryotic species from the human gut. These genomes contain over 625 million protein sequences used to generate the Unified Human Gastrointestinal Protein (UHGP) catalogue, a collection that more than doubles the number of gut protein clusters over the Integrated Gene Catalogue. We find that a large portion of the human gut microbiome remains to be fully explored, with over 70% of the UHGG species lacking cultured representatives, and 40% of the UHGP missing meaningful functional annotations. Intra-species genomic variation analyses revealed a large reservoir of accessory genes and single-nucleotide variants, many of which were specific to individual human populations. These freely available genomic resources should greatly facilitate investigations into the human gut microbiome.

isolation_comments: isolated from autochthonous microbiota present in a regional feed product
comments: Fermented feed is an agricultural practice used in worldwide to improve the growth performance of the farm animals. It is formed by the mixture of bacteria and yeasts that improve the quality of the raw material used in its preparation as well as the sensorial properties contributing also to the intestinal health of animals. In this study, we describe microorganisms isolated from autochthonous microbiota present in a regional feed product. Lactobacillus paracasei IBR07 (Lacticaseibacillus paracasei)can resist and persist at low pH. Therefore, potential pathways involved in acid response were analyzed to improve our knowledge in this response. This strain is considered safe for animal feed, and to be non-human pathogens, and we confirm these results explored in the Galleria mellonellasystem. Thus, the identification of species that can improve the final quality (sensorial and nutritional) of fermented feed constitutes a biotechnological challenge to increase animal production.

isolation_comments: isolated from dairy, plant, and human sources
comments: The broad ecological adaptability of Lactobacillus casei facilitates widespread application of this organism in the food and health industries.  To identify the genomic features of L. casei that contribute to evolution and lifestyle adaptation of the species, we performed comparative genomic analysis of 17 L. casei genomes representing strains isolated from dairy, plant, and human sources.  Gene gain, via acquisition of genomic islands, likely confers a fitness benefit in specific habitats.  The loss of unnecessary ancestral traits was especially pronounced in strains that show specialization for a cheese environment, where gene decay likely results in enhanced fitness in the dairy niche.  This study gives the first picture of the L. casei pangenome and provides valuable insights into evolution and lifestyle adaptation of this important bacterium.

comments: I order to study the mechanism underlying bile resistance of lactic acid bacteria, three strains of Lactobacillus paracasei were chosen. Strain NRIC0644 was originally isolated from fermented milk product, thereby of animal origin, whereas strains NRIC1917 and NRIC1981 were isolated from sugarcane wine and compost, respectively, thereby of vegetable origin. Preliminary test indicated vegetable-originated strains NRIC1917 and NRIC1981 were more resistant to cholate, the major component of bile compared to NRIC0644. The aim of the whole genome sequencing of these three strains was to elucidate the cause from which the difference in the bile resistance was brought about among these strains, and to find out common genetic feature for the bile resistant character. The information might be relevant for screening bile resistant lactic acid bacteria, which would contribute to develop useful probiotics.

genome_name: Lactobacillus paracasei subsp. paracasei strain ATCC 25302
comments: Owing to their unique potential to ferment carbohydrates, both homo- and heterofermentative lactic acid bacteria (LAB) are widely used in the food industry. Deciphering the genetic bases that determine the LAB fermentation type, and hence carbohydrate utilization, is paramount to optimize LAB industrial processes. Deep sequencing of 24 LAB species and comparison with 32 publicly available genome sequences provided a comparative data set including five major LAB genera for further analysis. Phylogenomic reconstruction confirmed Leuconostoc and Pediococcus species as independently emerging from the Lactobacillus genus, within one of the three phylogenetic clades identified. These clades partially grouped LABs according to their fermentation types, suggesting some metabolic capabilities were independently acquired during LAB evolution. In order to apply a genome-wide association study (GWAS) at the multigene family level, utilization of 49 carbohydrates was also profiled for these 56 LAB species. GWAS results indicated that obligately heterofermentative species lack 1-phosphofructokinase, required for D-mannose degradation in the homofermentative pathway. Heterofermentative species were found to often contain the araBAD operon, involved in L-arabinose degradation, which is important for heterofermentation. Taken together, our results provide helpful insights into the genetic determinants of LAB carbohydrate metabolism, and opens for further experimental research, aiming at validating the role of these candidate genes for industrial applications.

comments: Recently, bacterial communities (microbiota) have been discovered in the female bladder. Thus, the “sterile urine” paradigm is no longer valid. In an effort to provide a comprehensive view of the newly discovered female urinary microbiota (FUM), we have established an Enhanced Quantitative Urine Culture (EQUC) protocol. EQUC isolates bacteria from 75-90% of urine samples deemed ‘no growth’ by the standard clinical microbiology urine culture method. We have begun to sequence and annotate the genomes of these isolated bacteria.

Comprehensive reference data is essential for accurate taxonomic and functional characterisation of the human gut microbiome. Here we present the Unified Human Gastrointestinal Genome (UHGG) collection, a resource combining 286,997 genomes representing 4,644 prokaryotic species from the human gut. These genomes contain over 625 million protein sequences used to generate the Unified Human Gastrointestinal Protein (UHGP) catalogue, a collection that more than doubles the number of gut protein clusters over the Integrated Gene Catalogue. We find that a large portion of the human gut microbiome remains to be fully explored, with over 70% of the UHGG species lacking cultured representatives, and 40% of the UHGP missing meaningful functional annotations. Intra-species genomic variation analyses revealed a large reservoir of accessory genes and single-nucleotide variants, many of which were specific to individual human populations. These freely available genomic resources should greatly facilitate investigations into the human gut microbiome.

isolation_comments: derived bacterial genome collection provides the basis to improve the taxonomic classification resolution of metagenomic analysis, and to allow subsequent in vitro and in vivo experiments on host physiology and gut colonisation process
comments: The study investigates how early microbe exposure and the developing immune system influence subsequent health and developmental outcomes. Culturing efforts coupled with whole genome sequencing of the gastrointestinal bacteria can address key questions that are computationally non-trivial using shotgun metagenomics alone. This comprehensive gut microbiota-derived bacterial genome collection provides the basis to improve the taxonomic classification resolution of metagenomic analysis, and to allow subsequent in vitro and in vivo experiments on host physiology and gut colonisation process. To get a broad and comprehensive coverage of the gut microbiota, we cultivated bacterial species from human faecal samples on different selectice agar media and broth. Samples are whole-genome sequenced on Illumina X10 150bp PE. This data is part of a pre-publication release. For information on the proper use of pre-publication data shared by the Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute (including details of any publication moratoria), please see http://www.sanger.ac.uk/datasharing/;Bacterial Genome

comments: Increased awareness about the relation between food and health has resulted in the emergence of new term - "functional food". If fermentation was previously considered as a method of food preservation, fermented food is now considered as an important source of biologically active compounds. The goal of this project is to develop technologies for new fermented functional food products. For this, genomes of several microorganisms that can be used as starter cultures in fermentation was sequenced.

isolation_comments: isolated strains, Lactobacillus casei AMBR2, contained unique fimbriae enabling strong adherence to URT epithelium, inhibited the growth and virulence of several URT pathogens, and successfully colonized nasal epithelium of healthy volunteers
comments: While an increasing number of beneficial microbiome members is characterized for the human gut and vagina, beneficial microbes are underexplored for the human upper respiratory tract (URT). In this study, we demonstrate that taxa from the beneficial Lactobacillus genus might have a role as keystone species in the healthy URT. Several URT-specific Lactobacillus isolates were cultured, characterized, and further explored for their genetic and functional properties related to adaptation to the URT. Catalase genes were found in the identified Lactobacillus taxa, which is a unique feature within this mostly facultative anaerobic genus. Moreover, one of our isolated strains, Lactobacillus casei AMBR2, contained unique fimbriae enabling strong adherence to URT epithelium, inhibited the growth and virulence of several URT pathogens, and successfully colonized nasal epithelium of healthy volunteers. This study thus demonstrates that specific Lactobacillus taxa are adapted to the URT and could have a beneficial keystone function in this habitat.;Lactic acid bacterium isolated from a healthy human upper respiratory tract

Comprehensive reference data is essential for accurate taxonomic and functional characterisation of the human gut microbiome. Here we present the Unified Human Gastrointestinal Genome (UHGG) collection, a resource combining 286,997 genomes representing 4,644 prokaryotic species from the human gut. These genomes contain over 625 million protein sequences used to generate the Unified Human Gastrointestinal Protein (UHGP) catalogue, a collection that more than doubles the number of gut protein clusters over the Integrated Gene Catalogue. We find that a large portion of the human gut microbiome remains to be fully explored, with over 70% of the UHGG species lacking cultured representatives, and 40% of the UHGP missing meaningful functional annotations. Intra-species genomic variation analyses revealed a large reservoir of accessory genes and single-nucleotide variants, many of which were specific to individual human populations. These freely available genomic resources should greatly facilitate investigations into the human gut microbiome.

genome_name: Lactobacillus mudanjiangensis strain Lactobacillus mudanjiangensis AMBF197
comments: In this study the first genome sequences of strains of Lactobacillus mudanjiangensis are reported and analyzed. Since its first description in 2013, no other strains from this Lactobacillus species have been described in the literature. Here, whole-genome sequencing was performed on the type strain of L. mudanjiangensis to confirm whether some carrot juice isolates were indeed members of this species. Since L. mudanjiangensis was found to be a member of the L. plantarum group, their genome sequences were analyzed together with 300 publicly available assemblies of closely related L. plantarum group species using a pangenomics pipeline. This allowed to get more insights into the genomic features of this understudied Lactobacillus species.;The genome sequence of Lactobacillus mudanjiangensis strain AMBF197 isolated from spontaneously fermented carrot juice

isolation_comments: isolated from various food sources and different climatic regions were genetically characterized at subspecies level with recA gene based multiplex PCR amplifications and pulsed-field gel electrophoresis (PFGE), and next generation sequencing of the strains was done
comments: Lactobacillus plantarum strains isolated from various food sources and different climatic regions were genetically characterized at subspecies level with recA gene based multiplex PCR amplifications and pulsed-field gel electrophoresis (PFGE), and next generation sequencing of the strains was done. Five strains were identified as Lactobacillus plantarum AS-6, AS-7, AS-8, AS-9 and AS-10. Stress related proteins encoding genes were also identified in the probiotic strains, we hypothesized that the antimicrobial activity of Lactobacillus plantarum strains was associated with plantaricin biosynthesis gene clusters products, class II bacteriocins. Indeed, plantaricin biosynthesis gene clusters were identified i.e. bacteriocin operons plnEFI, plnABCD, regulatory operon plnA, transport operon plnGHSTUVW. All the strains were tested for the production of bacteriocin against major food borne pathogens (L. innocua and L. monocytogenes). Moreover, acid tolerance, NaCl tolerance, survival in simulated gastric juice, bile salt hydrolase activity, and antibiotic resistance of these strains were also analysed. Identification of gene encoding bacteriocin (plantaracin 423), along withenzyme sensitivity assays to protinease K and pepsin were also performed.

Owing to their unique potential to ferment carbohydrates, both homo- and heterofermentative lactic acid bacteria (LAB) are widely used in the food industry. Deciphering the genetic bases that determine the LAB fermentation type, and hence carbohydrate utilization, is paramount to optimize LAB industrial processes. Deep sequencing of 24 LAB species and comparison with 32 publicly available genome sequences provided a comparative data set including five major LAB genera for further analysis. Phylogenomic reconstruction confirmed Leuconostoc and Pediococcus species as independently emerging from the Lactobacillus genus, within one of the three phylogenetic clades identified. These clades partially grouped LABs according to their fermentation types, suggesting some metabolic capabilities were independently acquired during LAB evolution. In order to apply a genome-wide association study (GWAS) at the multigene family level, utilization of 49 carbohydrates was also profiled for these 56 LAB species. GWAS results indicated that obligately heterofermentative species lack 1-phosphofructokinase, required for D-mannose degradation in the homofermentative pathway. Heterofermentative species were found to often contain the araBAD operon, involved in L-arabinose degradation, which is important for heterofermentation. Taken together, our results provide helpful insights into the genetic determinants of LAB carbohydrate metabolism, and opens for further experimental research, aiming at validating the role of these candidate genes for industrial applications.

isolation_comments: isolated from the microbiota of fermented table olives
comments: Lactiplantibacillus pentosus includes strains used as starter or adjunct cultures in the production of several fermented foods. Specifically, Lactipl. pentosus and the closely related species Lactipl. plantarum and Lactipl. paraplantarum, are the dominant lactic acid bacteria (LAB) isolated from the microbiota of fermented table olives.Here, we report the draft genome sequence of Lactipl. pentosus O17, a strain isolated from olives brine (Bella di Cerignola cultivar), able to degrade oleuropein and to survive in presence of different phenolic compounds. The genome of Lactipl. pentosus O17 may be useful to improve the knowledge on the metabolism of phenolic compounds in lactic acid bacteria.

sequencing_centers: Iwahashi lab applied biological science, Gifu university
comments: Tea is one of the most popular beverages in the world, and there are many different types. Post-fermented teas which need microbial fermentation are locally produced in Asia. Awa-bancha, a type of post-fermented tea, is traditionally produced in Kamikatsu, Tokushima Prefecture. Previous research has demonstrated that two species of bacteria, L.plantarum and L.pentosus, are largely responsible for the fermentation of Awa-Bancha. Although the process varies slightly from each manufacturer, fermentation makes them the dominant species. These bacteria generate lactic acid, which enables them to obtain a unique acidity and flavour and improves the shortage ability of tea. This study will facilitate the understanding of microbial interactions, and why these are dominant species in the production of Awa-Bancha.

isolation_source: 5 day old mice colon contents using MRS selective media
isolation_comments: isolated from 5 day old mice colon contents using MRS selective media
comments: Neonatal late-onset sepsis is a devastating disease for which pre-term infants are highly susceptible. Using a novel murine model of this disease, we gained insights on how dysbiosis in neonatal mice is critically important to the susceptibility of this disease. To better understand the mechanisms by which the endogenous flora offer protection or susceptible to newborn mice, we aimed to better characterize several isolates from our colony. This BioSample contains the whole genome sequences of lactobacilli isolated from 5 day old mice colon contents using MRS selective media. Additionally, we have included a previously unsequenced probiotic and a previously unsequenced pathogen to better understand genetic determinants related to pathogenicity of K. pneumoniae in neonates and protection by probiotic lactobacilli.

isolation_comments: isolated from various food sources and different climatic regions were genetically characterized at subspecies level with recA gene based multiplex PCR amplifications and pulsed-field gel electrophoresis (PFGE), and next generation sequencing of the strains was done
comments: Lactobacillus plantarum strains isolated from various food sources and different climatic regions were genetically characterized at subspecies level with recA gene based multiplex PCR amplifications and pulsed-field gel electrophoresis (PFGE), and next generation sequencing of the strains was done. Five strains were identified as Lactobacillus plantarum AS-6, AS-7, AS-8, AS-9 and AS-10. Stress related proteins encoding genes were also identified in the probiotic strains, we hypothesized that the antimicrobial activity of Lactobacillus plantarum strains was associated with plantaricin biosynthesis gene clusters products, class II bacteriocins. Indeed, plantaricin biosynthesis gene clusters were identified i.e. bacteriocin operons plnEFI, plnABCD, regulatory operon plnA, transport operon plnGHSTUVW. All the strains were tested for the production of bacteriocin against major food borne pathogens (L. innocua and L. monocytogenes). Moreover, acid tolerance, NaCl tolerance, survival in simulated gastric juice, bile salt hydrolase activity, and antibiotic resistance of these strains were also analysed. Identification of gene encoding bacteriocin (plantaracin 423), along withenzyme sensitivity assays to protinease K and pepsin were also performed.

Comprehensive reference data is essential for accurate taxonomic and functional characterisation of the human gut microbiome. Here we present the Unified Human Gastrointestinal Genome (UHGG) collection, a resource combining 286,997 genomes representing 4,644 prokaryotic species from the human gut. These genomes contain over 625 million protein sequences used to generate the Unified Human Gastrointestinal Protein (UHGP) catalogue, a collection that more than doubles the number of gut protein clusters over the Integrated Gene Catalogue. We find that a large portion of the human gut microbiome remains to be fully explored, with over 70% of the UHGG species lacking cultured representatives, and 40% of the UHGP missing meaningful functional annotations. Intra-species genomic variation analyses revealed a large reservoir of accessory genes and single-nucleotide variants, many of which were specific to individual human populations. These freely available genomic resources should greatly facilitate investigations into the human gut microbiome.

isolation_comments: isolated from artisanal fermented food products in Laboratory of Antibiotic, Enzyme, Probiotic and Starter Culture Technologies, Faculty of Food Technology and Biotechnology University of Zagreb, only few of Lactobacillus strains are found to possess S-layer proteins on the cell surface, among which Lactobacillus helveticus M92, Lactobacillus brevis ZG1, Lactobacillus brevis SF9B and Lactobacillus brevis SF15B
comments: The research in the frame of Croatian Science Foundation project entitled „Probiotics and starter cultures – surface proteins and bacteriocins“ is aimed to deliver new generation of probiotics and functional starter cultures, thoughtfully characterised and with specific features such as production of functional surface (S)-layer proteins and bacteriocins with broad spectrum of activity towards potential food contaminants and pathogens. Among more than 200 different LAB strains isolated from artisanal fermented food products in Laboratory of Antibiotic, Enzyme, Probiotic and Starter Culture Technologies, Faculty of Food Technology and Biotechnology University of Zagreb, only few of Lactobacillus strains are found to possess S-layer proteins on the cell surface, among which Lactobacillus helveticus M92, Lactobacillus brevis ZG1, Lactobacillus brevis SF9B and Lactobacillus brevis SF15B. Importance of S-layer proteins lies in increasing scientific evidences that some probiotic properties of lactic acid bacteria (LAB), such as enhanced survival in rigorous conditions in gastrointestinal tract and during the process of freeze-drying, adhesion to intestinal epithelial cells or inhibition of pathogens, are related to the occurrence of those proteins. Hence, it is believed that the production of S-layer proteins might be a selective criterion indicating probiotic effect of Lactobacillus species that express those specific surface proteins. Another feature specific to certain strains of LAB, which gives them a selective advantage when applied as probiotic or starter cultures, is the production of bacteriocins. Among all the isolated autochthonous LAB, three Lactobaillus plantarum strains, M92C, SF15C and D13, showed advanced bacteriocinogenic potential. Besides their application as probiotics, these strains could be considered as starter cultures with potential to improve the functionality and quality of various fermented products, while in the same time preserving their traditional sensory characteristics.

Three Lactobacillus plantarum probiotic strains (Lp790, Lp813, and Lp998) of dairy origin showed the best probiotic potential (Zago et al., 2011) and were then studied in more detail in this study. The genome sequence of this three strains was determined using a Miseq Illumina system. Genome analysis of Lp790, Lp813, and Lp998 and comparative genomics provided insight into genes and gene cassettes involved in probiotic functions, including life-style adaptation, genome synteny. Genomic chracteristics were compared to in-vivo results, in which the immunomodulation properties using models to predict for in vivo efficacy, the capacity to produce B-group vitamins and to induce cytokine production by dendritic cells were tested to characterize probiotic potential of these strains.

isolation_comments: isolated from artisanal fermented food products in Laboratory of Antibiotic, Enzyme, Probiotic and Starter Culture Technologies, Faculty of Food Technology and Biotechnology University of Zagreb, only few of Lactobacillus strains are found to possess S-layer proteins on the cell surface, among which Lactobacillus helveticus M92, Lactobacillus brevis ZG1, Lactobacillus brevis SF9B and Lactobacillus brevis SF15B
comments: The research in the frame of Croatian Science Foundation project entitled „Probiotics and starter cultures – surface proteins and bacteriocins“ is aimed to deliver new generation of probiotics and functional starter cultures, thoughtfully characterised and with specific features such as production of functional surface (S)-layer proteins and bacteriocins with broad spectrum of activity towards potential food contaminants and pathogens. Among more than 200 different LAB strains isolated from artisanal fermented food products in Laboratory of Antibiotic, Enzyme, Probiotic and Starter Culture Technologies, Faculty of Food Technology and Biotechnology University of Zagreb, only few of Lactobacillus strains are found to possess S-layer proteins on the cell surface, among which Lactobacillus helveticus M92, Lactobacillus brevis ZG1, Lactobacillus brevis SF9B and Lactobacillus brevis SF15B. Importance of S-layer proteins lies in increasing scientific evidences that some probiotic properties of lactic acid bacteria (LAB), such as enhanced survival in rigorous conditions in gastrointestinal tract and during the process of freeze-drying, adhesion to intestinal epithelial cells or inhibition of pathogens, are related to the occurrence of those proteins. Hence, it is believed that the production of S-layer proteins might be a selective criterion indicating probiotic effect of Lactobacillus species that express those specific surface proteins. Another feature specific to certain strains of LAB, which gives them a selective advantage when applied as probiotic or starter cultures, is the production of bacteriocins. Among all the isolated autochthonous LAB, three Lactobaillus plantarum strains, M92C, SF15C and D13, showed advanced bacteriocinogenic potential. Besides their application as probiotics, these strains could be considered as starter cultures with potential to improve the functionality and quality of various fermented products, while in the same time preserving their traditional sensory characteristics.
Understanding the evolution of L. plantarum

isolation_comments: isolated strains, Lactobacillus casei AMBR2, contained unique fimbriae enabling strong adherence to URT epithelium, inhibited the growth and virulence of several URT pathogens, and successfully colonized nasal epithelium of healthy volunteers
comments: While an increasing number of beneficial microbiome members is characterized for the human gut and vagina, beneficial microbes are underexplored for the human upper respiratory tract (URT). In this study, we demonstrate that taxa from the beneficial Lactobacillus genus might have a role as keystone species in the healthy URT. Several URT-specific Lactobacillus isolates were cultured, characterized, and further explored for their genetic and functional properties related to adaptation to the URT. Catalase genes were found in the identified Lactobacillus taxa, which is a unique feature within this mostly facultative anaerobic genus. Moreover, one of our isolated strains, Lactobacillus casei AMBR2, contained unique fimbriae enabling strong adherence to URT epithelium, inhibited the growth and virulence of several URT pathogens, and successfully colonized nasal epithelium of healthy volunteers. This study thus demonstrates that specific Lactobacillus taxa are adapted to the URT and could have a beneficial keystone function in this habitat.;Lactic acid bacterium isolated from a healthy human upper respiratory tract

isolation_comments: isolated from virgin coconut oil
comments: Virgin coconut oil (VCO) is an essential oil for the industry in Southeast Asia, and it made by fermentation by bacteria. Lactic acid bacteria are one of the common bacteria species used for the fermentation of coconut milk to produce VCO. During the fermentation, lactic acid bacteria produce organic acid, hydrogen peroxide and bacteriocin. However, lactic acid and bacteriocin productivity are changed in acidity and salinity. In this study, we assess the productivity under saline stress condition, pH and temperature by L. plantarum isolated from virgin coconut oil. We isolated L. plantarum COY 2906 from VCO and identified genome sequence because the genetical approach facilities to understand the mechanism of bacteriocin production.

genome_name: Lactobacillus plantarum strain L. plantarum A6
comments: The objective of this work was to investigate the nutritional potential of L. plantarum A6 in a food matrix using next generation sequencing . For this purpose, we first sequenced characterize the genome of this strain, in order to have the most complete overview of as possible of thits potential. Then, we compared the its transcriptome of the strain L. plantarum A6when grown in a food matrix made from pearl millet to its transcriptome when the strain is cultivated into culture medium using next generation sequencing. Genomic comparison with the strains L. plantarum WCFS1, ST-III, JDM1 and ATCC14917 allowed the identification of 362 coding sequences specific to L. plantarum A6. Furthermore, Ggenes coding important functions important for nutritional quality of the food have also been identified:, such as those involved in metabolism of polyphenols , have been identified. Some complete biosynthetic biosynthesis pathways such asof folate among others.and their expression has been characterized. In addition, Cconsidering its interest as efficiency as an amylolytic bacteriastrain, we investigated all genes involved in carbohydrate metabolism, giving special attention to starch metabolism. An extracellular alpha amylase, a neopullulanase and the maltodextrin transporters are were identified and were all highly expressed in food matrix.The combination of genomic and transcriptomic not only revealed undocumented nutritional properties of L. plantarum A6, but also documented the behaviour of this bacteria in food.

comments: Lactobacillus plantarum 16 was isolated during a large scale screen to identify lactic acid bacterial strains with antifungal activitites. It was shown to have broad-spectrum antifungal activities towards a variety of food-spoilage fungi and has been successfully used as a biopreservative in a number of food models to extend product shelf life. The genome sequence of Lb. plantarum 16 can be used as a basis to discern the machinery involved in antifungal production.

Comprehensive reference data is essential for accurate taxonomic and functional characterisation of the human gut microbiome. Here we present the Unified Human Gastrointestinal Genome (UHGG) collection, a resource combining 286,997 genomes representing 4,644 prokaryotic species from the human gut. These genomes contain over 625 million protein sequences used to generate the Unified Human Gastrointestinal Protein (UHGP) catalogue, a collection that more than doubles the number of gut protein clusters over the Integrated Gene Catalogue. We find that a large portion of the human gut microbiome remains to be fully explored, with over 70% of the UHGG species lacking cultured representatives, and 40% of the UHGP missing meaningful functional annotations. Intra-species genomic variation analyses revealed a large reservoir of accessory genes and single-nucleotide variants, many of which were specific to individual human populations. These freely available genomic resources should greatly facilitate investigations into the human gut microbiome.

The complete genome sequences of several pairs of closely related prokaryotes are now available. Surprisingly, even strains of the same species can differ by as much as 20 % in gene content. Several analyses of very closely related genomes comparisons reported over the last years show that there may be as much to learn about diversity. Extensive genomic comparisons are possible not only between representatives of distant evolutionary phyla, but also between species of the same phylogenetic branch where individual evolutionary events can be more readily identified. They also indicate that sequencing of one representative genome give us nowhere near a complete picture of the genetic repertoire of any species, and that new and comparative methods will be required. Remarkable innovation in sequencing technologies has been achieved making them high-throughput, faster and more cost effective. The sequencing field has experienced a major shift by the introduction of innovation sequencing technologies capable of generating sequence data at a fraction of the cost and much quicker when compared to the Sanger method. Bacteria are characterized by extensive intraspecies variation. There is not only the sequence variation found in all species, but also the presence or absence of whole genes or clusters of genes. We propose to apply the sequencing technology developed by Illumina on several strains of Lactobacillus acidophilus and helveticus to enable a comparative study that will link genotype and phenotype at the genomic level.

Owing to their unique potential to ferment carbohydrates, both homo- and heterofermentative lactic acid bacteria (LAB) are widely used in the food industry. Deciphering the genetic bases that determine the LAB fermentation type, and hence carbohydrate utilization, is paramount to optimize LAB industrial processes. Deep sequencing of 24 LAB species and comparison with 32 publicly available genome sequences provided a comparative data set including five major LAB genera for further analysis. Phylogenomic reconstruction confirmed Leuconostoc and Pediococcus species as independently emerging from the Lactobacillus genus, within one of the three phylogenetic clades identified. These clades partially grouped LABs according to their fermentation types, suggesting some metabolic capabilities were independently acquired during LAB evolution. In order to apply a genome-wide association study (GWAS) at the multigene family level, utilization of 49 carbohydrates was also profiled for these 56 LAB species. GWAS results indicated that obligately heterofermentative species lack 1-phosphofructokinase, required for D-mannose degradation in the homofermentative pathway. Heterofermentative species were found to often contain the araBAD operon, involved in L-arabinose degradation, which is important for heterofermentation. Taken together, our results provide helpful insights into the genetic determinants of LAB carbohydrate metabolism, and opens for further experimental research, aiming at validating the role of these candidate genes for industrial applications.

genome_name: Lactobacillus crispatus strain FDAARGOS_743 strain Not applicable
comments: In May 2014, the FDA and collaborators established a publicly available dAtabase for Reference Grade micrObial Sequences called FDA-ARGOS. With funding support from FDA’s Office of Counterterrorism and Emerging Threats (OCET) and DoD, the FDA-ARGOS team are initially collecting and sequencing 2000 microbes that include biothreat microorganisms, common clinical pathogens and closely related species. Currently, FDA-ARGOS microbial genomes are generated in 3 phases. Generally:  Phase 1 entails collection of a previously identified microbe and nucleic acid extraction. Phase 2, the microbial nucleic acids are sequenced and de novo assembled using Illumina and PacBio sequencing platforms at the Institute for Genome Sciences at the University of Maryland (UMD-IGS). Phase 3, the assembled genomes are vetted by an ID-NGS subject matter expert working group consisting of FDA personnel and collaborators and the data are deposited in NCBI databases.   The FDA-ARGOS genomes meet the quality metrics for reference-grade genomes for regulatory use. FDA-ARGOS reference genomes have been de novo assembled with high depth of base coverage and placed within a pre-established phylogenetic tree. Each microbial isolate in the database is covered at a minimum of 20X over 95 percent of the assembled core genome. Furthermore, sample specific metadata, raw reads, assemblies, annotation and details of the bioinformatics pipeline are available.

Comprehensive reference data is essential for accurate taxonomic and functional characterisation of the human gut microbiome. Here we present the Unified Human Gastrointestinal Genome (UHGG) collection, a resource combining 286,997 genomes representing 4,644 prokaryotic species from the human gut. These genomes contain over 625 million protein sequences used to generate the Unified Human Gastrointestinal Protein (UHGP) catalogue, a collection that more than doubles the number of gut protein clusters over the Integrated Gene Catalogue. We find that a large portion of the human gut microbiome remains to be fully explored, with over 70% of the UHGG species lacking cultured representatives, and 40% of the UHGP missing meaningful functional annotations. Intra-species genomic variation analyses revealed a large reservoir of accessory genes and single-nucleotide variants, many of which were specific to individual human populations. These freely available genomic resources should greatly facilitate investigations into the human gut microbiome.

Antibiotic resistance (AR) has already become a public concern that has major impacts on human health. The AR profile in agricultural related environment, especially the gut microbiota of farm animals, is possibly a critical route for AR dissemination along the food chain. AR genes and antibiotic resistant (ART) bacterial have been detected in the gut microbiome of farm animals even without direct exposure to antibiotic. Previous study has revealed that the acquisition of ART bacteria and AR genes impacts the shift of microbial composition and resistome in the gut microbiota. Therefore microbial interference by AR-free probiotic may achieve double goals, AR elimination in the gut microbiota and health promotion. The object of this project is to develop new probiotic strains that have AR elimination functions.

genome_name: Lactobacillus delbrueckii subsp. jakobsenii strain DSM 26046
comments: Owing to their unique potential to ferment carbohydrates, both homo- and heterofermentative lactic acid bacteria (LAB) are widely used in the food industry. Deciphering the genetic bases that determine the LAB fermentation type, and hence carbohydrate utilization, is paramount to optimize LAB industrial processes. Deep sequencing of 24 LAB species and comparison with 32 publicly available genome sequences provided a comparative data set including five major LAB genera for further analysis. Phylogenomic reconstruction confirmed Leuconostoc and Pediococcus species as independently emerging from the Lactobacillus genus, within one of the three phylogenetic clades identified. These clades partially grouped LABs according to their fermentation types, suggesting some metabolic capabilities were independently acquired during LAB evolution. In order to apply a genome-wide association study (GWAS) at the multigene family level, utilization of 49 carbohydrates was also profiled for these 56 LAB species. GWAS results indicated that obligately heterofermentative species lack 1-phosphofructokinase, required for D-mannose degradation in the homofermentative pathway. Heterofermentative species were found to often contain the araBAD operon, involved in L-arabinose degradation, which is important for heterofermentation. Taken together, our results provide helpful insights into the genetic determinants of LAB carbohydrate metabolism, and opens for further experimental research, aiming at validating the role of these candidate genes for industrial applications.

isolation_comments: isolated from cow milk in 1993, in Buenos Aires, Argentina
comments: The L delbrueckii CIDCA 133 is a probiotic bacterium isolated from cow milk in 1993, in Buenos Aires, Argentina. This strain was hugely studied. The invitro test revealed the resistance of this strain to high acid and bile concentrations and the ability to inhibit the growth of food contaminants and pathogenic microorganisms such as enterohemorragic E. coli. In addition, the CIDCA 133 strain, was able to decrease harmful bacterial enzymatic activities such as nitrate reductase and its resistance to the the inhibitory cationic effectors of the innate immune system in cultured human enterocytes, and also was showed the ability of this strain to stimulate the phagocytosis, induces reactive oxygen species (ROS and NO), and promotes expression of surface markers related to antigen presentation. Recently a fermented milk by this bacterium was assayed in a mucositis murine model. The L. delbrueckii CIDCA consumption during 13 consecutive days showed the protective effect on intestinal mucosa damage with significant reduction of time-course weight\; prevention in intestinal shortening and reduced levels of sIgA, MPO and EPO enzymatic activity. It was also observed reduction in the intestinal permeability induced by 5-FU drugs and the histologic parameters presented ameliorating in the intestinal mucosal damage.

In this study we therefore cultured and sequenced isolates from chicken caecum among which we identified isolates belonging to 6 different phyla including Firmicutes, Bacteroidetes, Actinobacteria, Proteobacteria, Verrucomicrobia, Elusimicrobia and Synergistetes.

sequencing_centers: The Edison Family Center of Genome Sciences and Systems Biology
comments: We illustrate an approach for integrating preclinical gnotobiotic animal models with human studies to understand the contributions of impaired gut microbial community development to childhood undernutrition. Combining metabolomic and proteomic analyses of serially collected plasma samples with metagenomic analyses of fecal samples, we characterized the biological state of Bangladeshi children with severe acute malnutrition (SAM) as they transitioned, following standard treatment, to moderate acute malnutrition (MAM) with persistent microbiota immaturity. Gnotobiotic mice were subsequently colonized with a defined consortium of bacterial strains representing different stages of microbiota development in healthy children. Administering different combinations of Bangladeshi complementary food ingredients to colonized and germ-free mice revealed diet-dependent changes in the relative abundance and metabolism of weaning-phase bacterial taxa underrepresented in SAM and MAM microbiota, plus diet- and colonization-dependent effects on host metabolism and growth-associated signaling pathways. Host and microbial effects of microbiota-directed complementary food (MDCF) prototypes were subsequently examined in gnotobiotic mice colonized with post-SAM MAM microbiota and in gnotobiotic piglets colonized with a defined consortium of targeted age- and growth-discriminatory bacteria. Finally, a randomized, double-blind study identified a lead MDCF that changes the abundances of targeted bacterial taxa and increases plasma levels of biomarkers and mediators of growth, bone formation, neurodevelopment, and immune function.

Comprehensive reference data is essential for accurate taxonomic and functional characterisation of the human gut microbiome. Here we present the Unified Human Gastrointestinal Genome (UHGG) collection, a resource combining 286,997 genomes representing 4,644 prokaryotic species from the human gut. These genomes contain over 625 million protein sequences used to generate the Unified Human Gastrointestinal Protein (UHGP) catalogue, a collection that more than doubles the number of gut protein clusters over the Integrated Gene Catalogue. We find that a large portion of the human gut microbiome remains to be fully explored, with over 70% of the UHGG species lacking cultured representatives, and 40% of the UHGP missing meaningful functional annotations. Intra-species genomic variation analyses revealed a large reservoir of accessory genes and single-nucleotide variants, many of which were specific to individual human populations. These freely available genomic resources should greatly facilitate investigations into the human gut microbiome.

Mouse models are essential for biomedical science and drug discovery, yet it is not known how the bacteria in the mouse microbiota – important determinants of phenotypes of health and disease – affect their relevance to human disease. To interrogate the taxonomic and functional differences between the human and mouse gut microbiotas, we developed the Mouse Gastrointestinal Bacteria Catalogue (MGBC). This project contains the genome assemblies for the 276 cultured isolates of the MGBC, termed the Mouse Culture Collection.

genome_name: Lactobacillus jensenii strain FDAARGOS_749 strain Not applicable
comments: In May 2014, the FDA and collaborators established a publicly available dAtabase for Reference Grade micrObial Sequences called FDA-ARGOS. With funding support from FDA’s Office of Counterterrorism and Emerging Threats (OCET) and DoD, the FDA-ARGOS team are initially collecting and sequencing 2000 microbes that include biothreat microorganisms, common clinical pathogens and closely related species. Currently, FDA-ARGOS microbial genomes are generated in 3 phases. Generally:  Phase 1 entails collection of a previously identified microbe and nucleic acid extraction. Phase 2, the microbial nucleic acids are sequenced and de novo assembled using Illumina and PacBio sequencing platforms at the Institute for Genome Sciences at the University of Maryland (UMD-IGS). Phase 3, the assembled genomes are vetted by an ID-NGS subject matter expert working group consisting of FDA personnel and collaborators and the data are deposited in NCBI databases.   The FDA-ARGOS genomes meet the quality metrics for reference-grade genomes for regulatory use. FDA-ARGOS reference genomes have been de novo assembled with high depth of base coverage and placed within a pre-established phylogenetic tree. Each microbial isolate in the database is covered at a minimum of 20X over 95 percent of the assembled core genome. Furthermore, sample specific metadata, raw reads, assemblies, annotation and details of the bioinformatics pipeline are available.

isolation_comments: isolated from 5 day old mice colon contents using MRS selective media
comments: Neonatal late-onset sepsis is a devastating disease for which pre-term infants are highly susceptible. Using a novel murine model of this disease, we gained insights on how dysbiosis in neonatal mice is critically important to the susceptibility of this disease. To better understand the mechanisms by which the endogenous flora offer protection or susceptible to newborn mice, we aimed to better characterize several isolates from our colony. This BioSample contains the whole genome sequences of lactobacilli isolated from 5 day old mice colon contents using MRS selective media. Additionally, we have included a previously unsequenced probiotic and a previously unsequenced pathogen to better understand genetic determinants related to pathogenicity of K. pneumoniae in neonates and protection by probiotic lactobacilli.

To interrogate the taxonomic and functional differences between the human and mouse gut microbiotas, we developed the Mouse Gastrointestinal Bacteria Catalogue (MGBC). This project contains the genome assemblies for the 276 cultured isolates of the MGBC, termed the Mouse Culture Collection.

Comprehensive reference data is essential for accurate taxonomic and functional characterisation of the human gut microbiome. Here we present the Unified Human Gastrointestinal Genome (UHGG) collection, a resource combining 286,997 genomes representing 4,644 prokaryotic species from the human gut. These genomes contain over 625 million protein sequences used to generate the Unified Human Gastrointestinal Protein (UHGP) catalogue, a collection that more than doubles the number of gut protein clusters over the Integrated Gene Catalogue. comments: Recently, bacterial communities (microbiota) have been discovered in the female bladder. Thus, the “sterile urine” paradigm is no longer valid. In an effort to provide a comprehensive view of the newly discovered female urinary microbiota (FUM), we have established an Enhanced Quantitative Urine Culture (EQUC) protocol. EQUC isolates bacteria from 75-90% of urine samples deemed ‘no growth’ by the standard clinical microbiology urine culture method. We have begun to sequence and annotate the genomes of these isolated bacteria.

comments: Lactobacillus gasseri K7 is an isolate from a child¿¿¿¿¿¿¿s faeces with in vitro and in vivo established probiotic properties. The gassericins K7 A (gassericin K7A [GenBank: EF392861]) and K7 B (gassericin K7 B [GenBank: AY307382]) produced by this strain are particularly interesting due to a wide range of activity against Gram-positive bacteria.

Owing to their unique potential to ferment carbohydrates, both homo- and heterofermentative lactic acid bacteria (LAB) are widely used in the food industry. Deciphering the genetic bases that determine the LAB fermentation type, and hence carbohydrate utilization, is paramount to optimize LAB industrial processes. Deep sequencing of 24 LAB species and comparison with 32 publicly available genome sequences provided a comparative data set including five major LAB genera for further analysis. Phylogenomic reconstruction confirmed Leuconostoc and Pediococcus species as independently emerging from the Lactobacillus genus, within one of the three phylogenetic clades identified. These clades partially grouped LABs according to their fermentation types, suggesting some metabolic capabilities were independently acquired during LAB evolution. In order to apply a genome-wide association study (GWAS) at the multigene family level, utilization of 49 carbohydrates was also profiled for these 56 LAB species. GWAS results indicated that obligately heterofermentative species lack 1-phosphofructokinase, required for D-mannose degradation in the homofermentative pathway. Heterofermentative species were found to often contain the araBAD operon, involved in L-arabinose degradation, which is important for heterofermentation. Taken together, our results provide helpful insights into the genetic determinants of LAB carbohydrate metabolism, and opens for further experimental research, aiming at validating the role of these candidate genes for industrial applications.

Prebiotics, selective dietary ingredients, promote the growth of beneficial gut microbiota conferring health benefits on the host. Artificial sweeteners are implicated in having prebiotic effects\; however, the molecular mechanisms underlying these effects have not been elucidated. Here we demonstrate alterations in composition and diversity of gut microbiota in piglets consuming feed containing the artificial sweetener SUCRAM (consisting of neohesperidin dihydrochalcone and saccharin), with the most notable change being a significant increase in abundance of gut Lactobacillaceae. In vitro analysis of lactobacillus growth characteristics and sugar transporter gene expression shows that neohesperidin dihydrochalcone reduces the lag phase of growth and enhances expression of sugar transporters. This increases the capacity for sugar uptake, explaining the in vivo effect of NHDC in promoting Lactobacillaceae populations. This study describes a novel mode of action of an artificial sweetener and its prebiotic potential in enhancing the growth of health promoting gut microbiota.

comments: In present study, we studied on soil samples collected from various areas in South Korea as sources to isolate novel bacteria and a strain NIBRBAC000499792 was isolated from Cheonan area located in the middle of Korean Peninsula. 16S rRNA gene sequence study of the strain NIBRBAC000499792 with closely related various Lactobacillus species revealed that the isolated strain NIBRBAC000499792 might be a novel species of Genus Lactobacillus. Comprehensive reference data is essential for accurate taxonomic and functional characterisation of the human gut microbiome. Here we present the Unified Human Gastrointestinal Genome (UHGG) collection, a resource combining 286,997 genomes representing 4,644 prokaryotic species from the human gut. These genomes contain over 625 million protein sequences used to generate the Unified Human Gastrointestinal Protein (UHGP) catalogue, a collection that more than doubles the number of gut protein clusters over the Integrated Gene Catalogue. We find that a large portion of the human gut microbiome remains to be fully explored, with over 70% of the UHGG species lacking cultured representatives, and 40% of the UHGP missing meaningful functional annotations. Intra-species genomic variation analyses revealed a large reservoir of accessory genes and single-nucleotide variants, many of which were specific to individual human populations. These freely available genomic resources should greatly facilitate investigations into the human gut microbiome.

isolation_comments: isolated strains, Lactobacillus casei AMBR2, contained unique fimbriae enabling strong adherence to URT epithelium, inhibited the growth and virulence of several URT pathogens, and successfully colonized nasal epithelium of healthy volunteers
comments: While an increasing number of beneficial microbiome members is characterized for the human gut and vagina, beneficial microbes are underexplored for the human upper respiratory tract (URT). In this study, we demonstrate that taxa from the beneficial Lactobacillus genus might have a role as keystone species in the healthy URT. Several URT-specific Lactobacillus isolates were cultured, characterized, and further explored for their genetic and functional properties related to adaptation to the URT. Catalase genes were found in the identified Lactobacillus taxa, which is a unique feature within this mostly facultative anaerobic genus. Moreover, one of our isolated strains, Lactobacillus casei AMBR2, contained unique fimbriae enabling strong adherence to URT epithelium, inhibited the growth and virulence of several URT pathogens, and successfully colonized nasal epithelium of healthy volunteers. This study thus demonstrates that specific Lactobacillus taxa are adapted to the URT and could have a beneficial keystone function in this habitat.;Lactic acid bacterium isolated from a healthy human upper respiratory tract

comments: Owing to their unique potential to ferment carbohydrates, both homo- and heterofermentative lactic acid bacteria (LAB) are widely used in the food industry. Deciphering the genetic bases that determine the LAB fermentation type, and hence carbohydrate utilization, is paramount to optimize LAB industrial processes. Deep sequencing of 24 LAB species and comparison with 32 publicly available genome sequences provided a comparative data set including five major LAB genera for further analysis. Phylogenomic reconstruction confirmed Leuconostoc and Pediococcus species as independently emerging from the Lactobacillus genus, within one of the three phylogenetic clades identified. These clades partially grouped LABs according to their fermentation types, suggesting some metabolic capabilities were independently acquired during LAB evolution. In order to apply a genome-wide association study (GWAS) at the multigene family level, utilization of 49 carbohydrates was also profiled for these 56 LAB species. GWAS results indicated that obligately heterofermentative species lack 1-phosphofructokinase, required for D-mannose degradation in the homofermentative pathway. Heterofermentative species were found to often contain the araBAD operon, involved in L-arabinose degradation, which is important for heterofermentation. Taken together, our results provide helpful insights into the genetic determinants of LAB carbohydrate metabolism, and opens for further experimental research, aiming at validating the role of these candidate genes for industrial applications.

The phyllosphere is the above-ground surface of plants which is in contact with the atmosphere. Similar to other plant surfaces, the phyllosphere is occupied by a diverse community of bacteria, fungi and other micro-organisms. Bacteria are the most abundant of these microbes and their cell count ranges between 10^6 to 10^7 cells per square cm of leaf surface. Phyllosphere microorganisms possess a wide range of adaptation and biocontrol factors, which allow them to adapt to the phyllosphere environment and inhibit the growth of microbial pathogens, thus sustaining plant health. Compost teas, the products of fermenting organic material in water, are another source of beneficial microbes to improve plant health. Furthermore, the large surface area and diversity of microbes on the phyllosphere makes this environment interesting for the bioremediation of air pollution. This study aims to gain insights into the taxonomic composition of a healthy phyllosphere microbiome, and of compost teas. Next, the adaptation, biocontrol, and bioremediation factors of potential beneficial bacteria are analysed.

comments: Lactobacillus curieae NBRC 111893 was found and isolated from k??so, a Japanese sugar-vegetable fermented beverage. Whole-genome sequencing of L. curieae NBRC 111893 was performed using an Ion Torrent PGM system. The resulting draft genome sequence is 1,971,719 bp with an average G+C content of 37.9%, and 21 contigs are assembled with a N50 length value of 471,655 bp. The draft genome of L. curieae NBRC 111893, annotated by the RAST server using Glimmer3, contains 2,592 candidate open reading frames, three rRNA genes, and 53 tRNA genes.

isolation_comments: isolated from modified atmosphere packaged cooked ham manufactured by different European producers during the product shelf-life
comments: 16 strains of Leuconostoc were isolated from modified atmosphere packaged cooked ham manufactured by different European producers during the product shelf-life. For this work, their genomes have been analyzed through whole genome sequencing, genes have been annotated and clustered into functional categories using RAST. Their pangenome was calculated with Roary. In order to identify bacteriocin-producing strains effective against Listeria monocytogenes, both on plate tests and in silico analysis using BAGEL4 were conducted. This work aims to study the genetic variability of Leuconostoc due to its role as bioprotective starter in meat industry.

Genome analysis of Leuconostoc citreum WiKim0096

Owing to their unique potential to ferment carbohydrates, both homo- and heterofermentative lactic acid bacteria (LAB) are widely used in the food industry. Deciphering the genetic bases that determine the LAB fermentation type, and hence carbohydrate utilization, is paramount to optimize LAB industrial processes. Deep sequencing of 24 LAB species and comparison with 32 publicly available genome sequences provided a comparative data set including five major LAB genera for further analysis. Phylogenomic reconstruction confirmed Leuconostoc and Pediococcus species as independently emerging from the Lactobacillus genus, within one of the three phylogenetic clades identified. These clades partially grouped LABs according to their fermentation types, suggesting some metabolic capabilities were independently acquired during LAB evolution. In order to apply a genome-wide association study (GWAS) at the multigene family level, utilization of 49 carbohydrates was also profiled for these 56 LAB species. GWAS results indicated that obligately heterofermentative species lack 1-phosphofructokinase, required for D-mannose degradation in the homofermentative pathway. Heterofermentative species were found to often contain the araBAD operon, involved in L-arabinose degradation, which is important for heterofermentation. Taken together, our results provide helpful insights into the genetic determinants of LAB carbohydrate metabolism, and opens for further experimental research, aiming at validating the role of these candidate genes for industrial applications.

genome_name: Leuconostoc falkenbergense strain FDAARGOS_1201 strain Not applicable
comments: In May 2014, the FDA and collaborators established a publicly available dAtabase for Reference Grade micrObial Sequences called FDA-ARGOS. With funding support from FDA’s Office of Counterterrorism and Emerging Threats (OCET) and DoD, the FDA-ARGOS team are initially collecting and sequencing 2000 microbes that include biothreat microorganisms, common clinical pathogens and closely related species. Currently, FDA-ARGOS microbial genomes are generated in 3 phases. Generally:  Phase 1 entails collection of a previously identified microbe and nucleic acid extraction. Phase 2, the microbial nucleic acids are sequenced and de novo assembled using Illumina and PacBio sequencing platforms at the Institute for Genome Sciences at the University of Maryland (UMD-IGS). Phase 3, the assembled genomes are vetted by an ID-NGS subject matter expert working group consisting of FDA personnel and collaborators and the data are deposited in NCBI databases.   The FDA-ARGOS genomes meet the quality metrics for reference-grade genomes for regulatory use. FDA-ARGOS reference genomes have been de novo assembled with high depth of base coverage and placed within a pre-established phylogenetic tree. Each microbial isolate in the database is covered at a minimum of 20X over 95 percent of the assembled core genome. Furthermore, sample specific metadata, raw reads, assemblies, annotation and details of the bioinformatics pipeline are available.

isolation_comments: isolated from modified atmosphere packaged cooked ham manufactured by different European producers during the product shelf-life
comments: 16 strains of Leuconostoc were isolated from modified atmosphere packaged cooked ham manufactured by different European producers during the product shelf-life. For this work, their genomes have been analyzed through whole genome sequencing, genes have been annotated and clustered into functional categories using RAST. Their pangenome was calculated with Roary. In order to identify bacteriocin-producing strains effective against Listeria monocytogenes, both on plate tests and in silico analysis using BAGEL4 were conducted. This work aims to study the genetic variability of Leuconostoc due to its role as bioprotective starter in meat industry.

The genomic data of Leuconostoc mesenteroides Wikim17 beloning to the family Leuconostocaceae of the phylum Firmicutes, were obtained using the MiSeq platform. The draft genome of Leuconostoc mesenteroides Wikim17 contains 1,859,317 bp. isolation_comments: isolated from different Montenegrin brine cheeses, in order to explore their diversity and provide genetic information for the selection of strains suitable for utilization as adjunct cultures in a future industrial cheese production
comments: Members of the genus Leuconostoc are Gram-positive, non-spore-forming, non-motile, and heterofermentative Lactic Acid Bacteria (LAB). Leuconostoc spp. are usually combined as an adjunct culture with fast acid producing Lactococcus sp. in undefined mixed (DL) type starter cultures. In many traditional dairy products, Leuconostoc spp. is a natural part of non-starter lactic acid bacteria (NSLAB), which play an important role in flavor development and therefore accounting for the typicity of cheeses. Despite the proven influence of Leuconostoc spp. on the final quality and characteristics of the product, data on the genomic diversity of Leuconostoc spp. isolates obtained from cheese are still scarce. Therefore, the focus of this study was the genomic characterization of Leuconostoc spp. isolated from different Montenegrin brine cheeses, in order to explore their diversity and provide genetic information for the selection of strains suitable for utilization as adjunct cultures in a future industrial cheese production.In spring and summer of 2019, sixteen Leuconostoc spp. isolates were obtained from white brine cheeses from nine different producers from three municipalities in the northern region of Montenegro. All isolates were identified as Ln. mesenteroides by MALDI-TOF-MS, digital DNA-DNA hybridization, 16s rDNA sequence analysis and ribosomal multilocus sequence typing (rMLST). Type Strain Server analysis (TYGS) assigned ten isolates to subspecies Ln. mesenteroides, and two each to Ln. cremoris, Ln. dextranicum and Ln. jonggajibkimchii, respectively. MLST and core genome MLST (cgMLST) revealed a high diversity of the Montenegrin Ln. mesenteroides cheese isolates. All isolates carried genes of the bacteriocin biosynthetic gene clusters, eight out of 16 strains carried the citCDEFG operon, 14 carried butA, and all 16 isolates carried alsS and ilv, genes responsible for the production of aromatic compounds. Safety evaluation indicated that isolates carried no virulence factors\; five carried plasmids, one strain carried a partial beta-lactamase gene, and one strain had a C656T transition in the 23S rRNA gene, conferring resistance to erythromycin and clindamycin.In conclusion, Ln. mesenteroides isolates from Montenegrin traditional cheeses, based on MLST and cgMLST displayed a high genetic diversity and, in addition, lacked close genetic relatedness to the isolates currently deposited in GenBank.

Comprehensive reference data is essential for accurate taxonomic and functional characterisation of the human gut microbiome. Here we present the Unified Human Gastrointestinal Genome (UHGG) collection, a resource combining 286,997 genomes representing 4,644 prokaryotic species from the human gut. These genomes contain over 625 million protein sequences used to generate the Unified Human Gastrointestinal Protein (UHGP) catalogue, a collection that more than doubles the number of gut protein clusters over the Integrated Gene Catalogue. We find that a large portion of the human gut microbiome remains to be fully explored, with over 70% of the UHGG species lacking cultured representatives, and 40% of the UHGP missing meaningful functional annotations. Intra-species genomic variation analyses revealed a large reservoir of accessory genes and single-nucleotide variants, many of which were specific to individual human populations. These freely available genomic resources should greatly facilitate investigations into the human gut microbiome.

genome_name: Leuconostoc pseudomesenteroides strain FDAARGOS_1003 strain Not applicable
comments: In May 2014, the FDA and collaborators established a publicly available dAtabase for Reference Grade micrObial Sequences called FDA-ARGOS. With funding support from FDA’s Office of Counterterrorism and Emerging Threats (OCET) and DoD, the FDA-ARGOS team are initially collecting and sequencing 2000 microbes that include biothreat microorganisms, common clinical pathogens and closely related species. Currently, FDA-ARGOS microbial genomes are generated in 3 phases. Generally:  Phase 1 entails collection of a previously identified microbe and nucleic acid extraction. Phase 2, the microbial nucleic acids are sequenced and de novo assembled using Illumina and PacBio sequencing platforms at the Institute for Genome Sciences at the University of Maryland (UMD-IGS). Phase 3, the assembled genomes are vetted by an ID-NGS subject matter expert working group consisting of FDA personnel and collaborators and the data are deposited in NCBI databases.   The FDA-ARGOS genomes meet the quality metrics for reference-grade genomes for regulatory use. FDA-ARGOS reference genomes have been de novo assembled with high depth of base coverage and placed within a pre-established phylogenetic tree. Each microbial isolate in the database is covered at a minimum of 20X over 95 percent of the assembled core genome. Furthermore, sample specific metadata, raw reads, assemblies, annotation and details of the bioinformatics pipeline are available.
Genomic features of bacteria were analyzed.

The FDA-ARGOS genomes meet the quality metrics for reference-grade genomes for regulatory use. FDA-ARGOS reference genomes have been de novo assembled with high depth of base coverage and placed within a pre-established phylogenetic tree. Each microbial isolate in the database is covered at a minimum of 20X over 95 percent of the assembled core genome. Furthermore, sample specific metadata, raw reads, assemblies, annotation and details of the bioinformatics pipeline are available.

isolation_comments: isolated from artisanal fermented food products in Laboratory of Antibiotic, Enzyme, Probiotic and Starter Culture Technologies, Faculty of Food Technology and Biotechnology University of Zagreb, only few of Lactobacillus strains are found to possess S-layer proteins on the cell surface, among which Lactobacillus helveticus M92, Lactobacillus brevis ZG1, Lactobacillus brevis SF9B and Lactobacillus brevis SF15B
comments: The research in the frame of Croatian Science Foundation project entitled „Probiotics and starter cultures – surface proteins and bacteriocins“ is aimed to deliver new generation of probiotics and functional starter cultures, thoughtfully characterised and with specific features such as production of functional surface (S)-layer proteins and bacteriocins with broad spectrum of activity towards potential food contaminants and pathogens. Among more than 200 different LAB strains isolated from artisanal fermented food products in Laboratory of Antibiotic, Enzyme, Probiotic and Starter Culture Technologies, Faculty of Food Technology and Biotechnology University of Zagreb, only few of Lactobacillus strains are found to possess S-layer proteins on the cell surface, among which Lactobacillus helveticus M92, Lactobacillus brevis ZG1, Lactobacillus brevis SF9B and Lactobacillus brevis SF15B. Importance of S-layer proteins lies in increasing scientific evidences that some probiotic properties of lactic acid bacteria (LAB), such as enhanced survival in rigorous conditions in gastrointestinal tract and during the process of freeze-drying, adhesion to intestinal epithelial cells or inhibition of pathogens, are related to the occurrence of those proteins. Hence, it is believed that the production of S-layer proteins might be a selective criterion indicating probiotic effect of Lactobacillus species that express those specific surface proteins. Another feature specific to certain strains of LAB, which gives them a selective advantage when applied as probiotic or starter cultures, is the production of bacteriocins. Among all the isolated autochthonous LAB, three Lactobaillus plantarum strains, M92C, SF15C and D13, showed advanced bacteriocinogenic potential. Besides their application as probiotics, these strains could be considered as starter cultures with potential to improve the functionality and quality of various fermented products, while in the same time preserving their traditional sensory characteristics.

Comprehensive reference data is essential for accurate taxonomic and functional characterisation of the human gut microbiome. Here we present the Unified Human Gastrointestinal Genome (UHGG) collection, a resource combining 286,997 genomes representing 4,644 prokaryotic species from the human gut. These genomes contain over 625 million protein sequences used to generate the Unified Human Gastrointestinal Protein (UHGP) catalogue, a collection that more than doubles the number of gut protein clusters over the Integrated Gene Catalogue. We find that a large portion of the human gut microbiome remains to be fully explored, with over 70% of the UHGG species lacking cultured representatives, and 40% of the UHGP missing meaningful functional annotations. Intra-species genomic variation analyses revealed a large reservoir of accessory genes and single-nucleotide variants, many of which were specific to individual human populations. These freely available genomic resources should greatly facilitate investigations into the human gut microbiome.

isolation_comments: isolated from 5 day old mice colon contents using MRS selective media
comments: Neonatal late-onset sepsis is a devastating disease for which pre-term infants are highly susceptible. Using a novel murine model of this disease, we gained insights on how dysbiosis in neonatal mice is critically important to the susceptibility of this disease. To better understand the mechanisms by which the endogenous flora offer protection or susceptible to newborn mice, we aimed to better characterize several isolates from our colony. This BioSample contains the whole genome sequences of lactobacilli isolated from 5 day old mice colon contents using MRS selective media. Additionally, we have included a previously unsequenced probiotic and a previously unsequenced pathogen to better understand genetic determinants related to pathogenicity of K. pneumoniae in neonates and protection by probiotic lactobacilli.

comments: N6-methyladenosine (m6A) is among the most common bacterial base modifications. Detection at single base resolution is possible using single-molecule sequencing with PacBio and more recently, nanopore sequencing. However, accuracy is variable and hasn't been well characterized across platforms. Here, we compare sites detected using PacBio data and SMRT Tools to those detected using nanopore data across eight species in a microbial reference community. We also use Illumina data from individual strains and the full community to generate and help validate assemblies for the reference community. With m6A sites validated using PacBio, we train and test a new neural network-based method to detect m6A from nanopore data and show it can improve detection depending on sequence context.

isolation_comments: isolated from artisanal fermented food products in Laboratory of Antibiotic, Enzyme, Probiotic and Starter Culture Technologies, Faculty of Food Technology and Biotechnology University of Zagreb, only few of Lactobacillus strains are found to possess S-layer proteins on the cell surface, among which Lactobacillus helveticus M92, Lactobacillus brevis ZG1, Lactobacillus brevis SF9B and Lactobacillus brevis SF15B
comments: The research in the frame of Croatian Science Foundation project entitled „Probiotics and starter cultures – surface proteins and bacteriocins“ is aimed to deliver new generation of probiotics and functional starter cultures, thoughtfully characterised and with specific features such as production of functional surface (S)-layer proteins and bacteriocins with broad spectrum of activity towards potential food contaminants and pathogens. Among more than 200 different LAB strains isolated from artisanal fermented food products in Laboratory of Antibiotic, Enzyme, Probiotic and Starter Culture Technologies, Faculty of Food Technology and Biotechnology University of Zagreb, only few of Lactobacillus strains are found to possess S-layer proteins on the cell surface, among which Lactobacillus helveticus M92, Lactobacillus brevis ZG1, Lactobacillus brevis SF9B and Lactobacillus brevis SF15B. Importance of S-layer proteins lies in increasing scientific evidences that some probiotic properties of lactic acid bacteria (LAB), such as enhanced survival in rigorous conditions in gastrointestinal tract and during the process of freeze-drying, adhesion to intestinal epithelial cells or inhibition of pathogens, are related to the occurrence of those proteins. Hence, it is believed that the production of S-layer proteins might be a selective criterion indicating probiotic effect of Lactobacillus species that express those specific surface proteins. Another feature specific to certain strains of LAB, which gives them a selective advantage when applied as probiotic or starter cultures, is the production of bacteriocins. Among all the isolated autochthonous LAB, three Lactobaillus plantarum strains, M92C, SF15C and D13, showed advanced bacteriocinogenic potential. Besides their application as probiotics, these strains could be considered as starter cultures with potential to improve the functionality and quality of various fermented products, while in the same time preserving their traditional sensory characteristics.

comments: Recently, bacterial communities (microbiota) have been discovered in the female bladder. Thus, the “sterile urine” paradigm is no longer valid. In an effort to provide a comprehensive view of the newly discovered female urinary microbiota (FUM), we have established an Enhanced Quantitative Urine Culture (EQUC) protocol. EQUC isolates bacteria from 75-90% of urine samples deemed ‘no growth’ by the standard clinical microbiology urine culture method. We have begun to sequence and annotate the genomes of these isolated bacteria.
